assumptions:
  - "OpenSSL::X509::Certificate objects built without signing or serialization are sufficient for SslChecker spec stubs (peer_cert.not_after and peer_cert.subject.to_s both work on a minimally-constructed instance)"
  - "Socket.tcp(host, port, connect_timeout:) is the correct Ruby stdlib entrypoint for timeout-bounded TCP connect (Ruby >= 2.6)"
  - "Timeout.timeout around OpenSSL::SSL::SSLSocket#connect may leak a file descriptor on async interrupt; the monitoring use case tolerates rare leaks and the ensure block closes sockets on the normal exit path"
  - "OpenSSL::SSL::SSLSocket requires #hostname= to be set for SNI before #connect, and test stubs that do not allow this setter will fail"

specifications:
  - "SslChecker.check(host:, port:) is a class method taking primitives; the dispatcher extracts host from URI.parse(site.url).host and passes site.tls_port as port"
  - "SSL cert classification (expired / <7 days / OK) lives in SslChecker, not PerformCheckJob — the documented ownership exception from decision 3 because the signal is temporal"
  - "SSL success returns CheckOutcome with error_message: nil, status_code: nil, body: nil, metadata: { cert_not_after:, cert_subject:, days_until_expiry: }"
  - "SSL failure (expired, expiring < 7 days, connection refused, handshake error, TLS error, handshake timeout, IpGuard block) returns error_message populated"
  - "IpGuard.check!(host) runs BEFORE any socket open so a blocked host never gets a TCP connect — regression proof: the spec stubs IpGuard to raise and asserts Socket.tcp was never called"
  - "PerformCheckJob#derive_status maps (error_message.nil? AND status_code.nil?) to :up for non-HTTP checks; HTTP retains its 200-399 check"
  - "Site validates tls_port presence and numericality (1..65_535) only when check_type is :ssl"
  - "Site#clear_irrelevant_config nulls tls_port on any non-:ssl save so stale config never hangs around after a check_type flip"
  - "CheckDispatcher#call now routes :ssl in addition to :http; the structural spec from Slice 2 still asserts public surface is exactly .call + UnknownCheckType"

deviations_from_plan: >
  Three files added to actual scope beyond the plan's Slice 3 declaration:
  app/jobs/perform_check_job.rb and spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb
  (the plan's prose describes derive_status handling SSL metadata but
  the bottom-of-slice file list omitted them; correctness required the
  nil status_code branch), and spec/components/site_form_component_spec.rb
  (the plan listed the preview but not the existing component spec, which
  needed new expectations for the check_type select and tls_port input).
  Not intent-drift — these are plan-bug fills covering the same concept
  (wire SSL end-to-end).

trade_offs: >
  Kept health classification for SSL (expired / <7 days / OK) inside SslChecker
  rather than PerformCheckJob.derive_status. This is the documented
  ownership asymmetry from decision 3 — SSL's signal is temporal and
  splitting it into job logic would require leaking metadata internals
  into the job. Cost: a Slice 10 reader needs to look in two places for
  "where does :degraded come from" (job for HTTP, checker for SSL). Mitigation:
  the plan's decision 3 text names this asymmetry explicitly and the
  Slice 10 scope will add the emission paths in both places.

  Used Timeout.timeout around OpenSSL::SSL::SSLSocket#connect for the
  10-second handshake bound. Technically unsafe (async interrupt can
  leak an FD), but the ensure block closes sockets on the normal exit
  path and the monitoring use case tolerates rare FD leaks better than
  it tolerates a stuck handshake hanging the job worker. The stdlib
  alternative — non-blocking I/O plus IO.select — is much more code for
  a check that runs on a 60s cadence.

  Left tls_port at DEFAULT_TLS_PORT=443 in the form's value= attribute
  rather than as a DB default. Cost: the form has to know about the
  default. Benefit: clear_irrelevant_config can unconditionally null
  the column for non-SSL sites without fighting a DB-level default,
  and the non-SSL rows stay explicitly nil rather than carrying
  leftover 443s.

interfaces:
  consumed:
    - "IpGuard.check!(host_or_ip) -> true | raises IpGuard::BlockedIpError"
    - "HttpChecker.check(url) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "CheckOutcome.new(status_code:, response_time_ms:, error_message:, checked_at:, body:, metadata:) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "Site#check_type -> String"
    - "Site#tls_port -> Integer | nil"
  published:
    - "SslChecker.check(host:, port:) -> CheckOutcome"
    - "CheckDispatcher.call(site) -> CheckOutcome | raises CheckDispatcher::UnknownCheckType"
    - "Site#ssl? -> Boolean"
    - "Site#tls_port= (integer writer)"
    - "Site::DEFAULT_TLS_PORT -> 443"

self_review:
  tests: >
    Added spec/services/ssl_checker_spec.rb with 8 cases (cert >7 days → up
    with metadata, cert <7 days → down with error_message, expired cert →
    down, IpGuard-blocked → down without opening a socket, connection refused
    → down, TLS handshake error → down, handshake timeout → down, and subject
    string round-trip). All cases stub Socket.tcp, OpenSSL::SSL::SSLSocket,
    and IpGuard — network-free per the plan's locked rule. Added an :ssl
    dispatch case to spec/services/check_dispatcher_spec.rb that asserts the
    host/port translation from URI.parse. Extended spec/models/site_spec.rb
    with tls_port validation and clear_irrelevant_config scrubbing. Added a
    nil-status_code success case to spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb that
    proves derive_status handles SSL-shaped results. Extended
    spec/components/site_form_component_spec.rb with check_type select and
    tls_port input assertions. Added a new_ssl_site preview variant.
  consistency: >
    SslChecker.check(host:, port:) mirrors HttpChecker.check(url) and the
    dispatcher pattern from Slice 2 — class method entrypoint, single instance
    method of the same name, private helpers below. The RECOVERABLE_ERRORS
    freeze-list pattern matches how BLOCKED_RANGES is declared in IpGuard.
    The form component gained fields inline rather than extracting per-type
    partials — that extraction is the Slice 4 trigger per the plan's Notes
    section, which explicitly said "at the first sign of branching on check_type
    in more than one spot (which happens in Slice 4 when TCP joins SSL), extract
    per-check-type partials IMMEDIATELY."
  metz: >
    Measured. ssl_checker.rb is 92 lines, 10 methods. check is 4 body lines
    plus a rescue clause; with_tls_socket is 5 body lines plus an ensure;
    classify is 2 body lines; days_until_expiry 1; cert_metadata 5 (single
    hash expression); cert_error 2; build_outcome 8 (single CheckOutcome.new
    expression); error_outcome 1; elapsed_ms 1. No method is flagrantly over
    the 5-line rule in statement count — the physically-longer methods are
    single expressions whose line count comes from multi-line hash or
    CheckOutcome construction. site.rb grew from 42 lines to 50 lines.
    check_dispatcher.rb grew from 23 to 27 lines (one new case branch).
    site_form_component.html.erb grew from 40 to 60 lines; Slice 4 will
    extract partials when TCP adds the second conditional field.
  duplication: >
    build_outcome in SslChecker deliberately parallels success_outcome in
    HttpChecker but is not shared — each checker will diverge in which
    fields it populates (content-match will add body, SSL populates
    metadata, etc.). Extracting a shared CheckOutcome factory now would
    be premature abstraction; Slice 6 will revisit if ContentMatchChecker
    needs something similar. The form error-display ERB block is duplicated
    across four field blocks — same as it was pre-Slice 3, will be addressed
    when Slice 4 extracts per-type partials.
  mocking: >
    Mocks all network boundaries: Socket.tcp, OpenSSL::SSL::SSLSocket,
    IpGuard.check!, and ssl_socket.peer_cert. Per the plan's rule, non-Faraday
    checker specs must stub external boundaries; the alternative (real TLS
    handshakes against localhost or a test server) makes specs flaky and
    slow. OpenSSL::X509::Certificate objects are constructed directly rather
    than mocked because they're owned stdlib types and the fake_cert helper
    sets only the fields the checker reads.
  error_paths: >
    RECOVERABLE_ERRORS enumerates eight exception classes. Each has an
    explicit spec case except Errno::EHOSTUNREACH and Errno::ENETUNREACH
    which are covered by the same code path as ECONNREFUSED (the rescue
    block treats all Errno descendants identically). Timeout::Error covers
    both the connect timeout (propagated from Socket.tcp) and the handshake
    timeout (from Timeout.timeout around ssl.connect). IpGuard::BlockedIpError
    has a dedicated spec case that also asserts Socket.tcp is never called.
  security: >
    IpGuard.check!(host) runs before the socket open, which is the correct
    order — the non-Faraday path now reuses the same range logic as the
    Faraday path. The DNS resolution happens inside IpGuard; SslChecker
    never looks up the host itself. The socket ensure block closes both
    TCP and SSL sockets on all paths including Timeout::Error, so no
    FD leaks on the normal control flow. Async interrupts during
    Timeout.timeout remain a known theoretical risk, documented in the
    class comment and the agent-note trade_offs.
  api: >
    Additive. SslChecker is a new published entrypoint. CheckDispatcher.call
    gains a new branch but the signature is unchanged. Site#tls_port and
    Site#ssl? are new. Site::DEFAULT_TLS_PORT is a new public constant.
    PerformCheckJob#derive_status is private; its new branch is internal.
    Backward compat: all existing Site records are check_type=:http after
    the Slice 2 migration and continue to work unchanged in this slice.
  performance: >
    SslChecker.check opens one TCP + one TLS socket per invocation with
    bounded timeouts (5s + 10s worst case). No caching, no pooling — a
    cert check on a 60s cadence is cheap enough that sharing sockets
    isn't worth the complexity. IpGuard.check! does at most one
    Resolv.getaddresses call, no new DNS traffic versus the HTTP path.
  dead_code: >
    None. The DEFAULT_TLS_PORT constant is referenced by the form component.
    RECOVERABLE_ERRORS is used in the rescue clause. All declared methods
    are called.

